        {
          "@id": "urn:uuid:d6c01219-bceb-5465-a33d-ac657c889b26",
          "@type": "uco-observable:ExtractedStringsFacet",
          "uco-observable:strings": [
            {
              "@id": "urn:uuid:a22fad30-b469-5a0b-a731-ffd61107dbcc",
              "@type": "uco-observable:ExtractedString",
              "uco-observable:stringValue": "UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT\nEASTERN DISTRICT OF WISCONSIN\n________________________________________________________________________\n\nUNITED STATES OF AMERICA,\nPlaintiff,\n\nvs. Case No. 25 CR 69\n\nBRADLEY D. HOUNSELL\nDefendant.\n_____________________________________________________________________\n\nSENTENCING MEMORANDUM\n_____________________________________________________________________\n\nBradley D. Hounsell, by counsel, hereby submits this Sentencing Memorandum. Based upon\nfactors outlined in 18 U.S.C.\u00a7 3553(a), Mr. Hounsell respectfully requests that the Court impose\na sentence of 120 months imprisonment. Counsel submits the following sentencing information\nand argument to support this request.\n\nI. PROCEDURAL HISTORY\n\nThe Pre-Sentence Report (PSR) represents an accurate procedural history of this case. The PSR\naccurately relates the offense conduct in paragraphs 14 through 49. The Philippine National\nPolice (PNP) Desiree Pampilo Jimenez, for the crime of sexually exploiting children online.\nDurning their investigation revealed that Ms. Jimenez victimized two of her sisters online, one who\nwas 14 years old and another who was 15 years old. The PNP specifically noted Ms. Jimenez offered\nan unsolicited pornographic show of the minors to Mr. Hounsell. Many of the messages were sexual\nin nature between the Mr. Hounsell and Ms. Jimenez, as he was interested in herself, an adult. It is\nunknown as to when these conversations between Ms. Jimenez and Mr. Hounsell started\nspeccifically. The actions of Ms. Jimenez where she offered the pornographic show of the minors\nappears to have started in June 2023. As referenced in paragraph 19 of the PSR, Mr. Hounsell\u2019s\ninitial response to Ms. Jimenez\u2019s offer was that the girl was young and later would indicate that he\nmay be interested in her when she becomes of age. Essentially, Mr. Hounsell never sought nor asked\nfor these young girls. His then predilection for sexual viewing of adult women now found himself\nviewing these young women as they were offered by Jimenez.\n\nMs. Jimenez and Mr. Hounsell continued these conversations very sporadically throughout 2023 and\nthen ended in January of 2024. Not to downplay the seriousness of the offense, but unlike other\npornography cases, this case by way of volume of evidence is minimal.\n\nCase 1:25-cr-00069-WCG Filed 05/12/26 Page 1 of 3 Document 31\nMr. Hounsell has no criminal history which results in a Criminal History score of zero with a\nCriminal History Category of I. The PSR calculates the base offense level at 32 with a two level\nincrease under U.S.S.G. \u00a7 2G1.3(c)(1) because the offense involved a minor who had attained\nthe age of 12 but not attained the age of 16, increase by 2 levels; pursuant to USSG\n\u00a72G2.1(b)(2)(A), two levels are added because the offense involved the commission of a sexual\nact; pursuant to USSG \u00a72G2.1(b)(4), if the offense involved material that portrays sadistic or\nmasochistic conduct or other depictions of violence, increase by 4 levels; and lastly pursuant to\nUSSG \u00a72G2.1(b)(6)(B), a 2-level increase is recommended because the offense involved the use\nof computer or interactive computer service for the purpose of transmitting material. The PSR\nalso includes a three-level decrease for a timely acceptance of responsibility. The total offense\nlevel for Mr. Hounsell is 39 which results in an advisory Sentencing Guideline Range of 262-327\nmonths imprisonment.\n\nII. APPLICABLE LAW\n\nThe Sentencing Guidelines are now \u201ceffectively advisory\u201d because of United States v. Booker,\n543 U.S. 220 (2005). While the Sentencing Court must still consider the Sentencing Guidelines\nwhen imposing a sentence, they now must also consider other factors as well including the\nfactors set forth in 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3553(a). Id.\nUnder \u00a7 3553(a), a Court shall \u201cimpose a sentence sufficient, but not greater than necessary, to\ncomply with the purposes\u201d of sentencing identified in paragraph 2 of the statute. Under\nparagraph 2, the sentence imposed should satisfy the following purposes:\n(a) to reflect the seriousness of the offense, to promote respect for the law,\n\nand to provide just punishment for the offense;\n(b) to afford adequate deterrence to criminal conduct;\n(c) to protect the public from further crimes of the defendant; and\n(d) to provide the defendant with needed educational or vocational\ntraining, medical care or other correctional treatment in the most\neffective manner.\nIn determining the particular sentence to be imposed, the court also must consider: (1) the nature\nand circumstance of the offense and the history and\ncharacteristics of the defendant; (2) the need for the sentence imposed to reflect\nparagraphs (a) through (d) above; (3) the kinds of sentences available; (4) the types\nof sentences and sentencing range established by the sentencing guidelines; (5)\nSentencing Commission policy statements; (6) the need to avoid unwarranted sentence\ndisparities among defendants with similar records who have found guilty of similar conduct; and\n(7) the need to provide restitution to any victims of the offense. 18 U.S.C \u00a73553(a).\n\nIII. ARGUMENT\n\na. Nature and Circumstances of the Case\n\nUnder 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3553 (a), it states the Court should consider the \u201cnature and circumstances of\nthe offense.\u201d\n\nb. History and Characteristics of the Defendant\n\nThe \u201chistory and characteristics of the defendant\u201d are considered as part of 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3553 (a).\nMr. Hounsell is 44 years old. He was born and raised in Wisconsin. Mr. Hounsell\u2019s personal and\nfamily data are addressed in paragraph\u2019s 75-90 in the PSR. Mr. Hounsell has used his time very\nCase 1:25-cr-00069-WCG Filed 05/12/26 Page 2 of 3 Document 31\nwisely since the date of his arrest to grow not only himself spiritually, but many of his family\nmembers. He has worked hard on his sobriety and has been sober for one year as he attends\nnumerous meetings at AA weekly. Mr. Hounsell\u2019s frame of mind has completely transformed\nstarting from the date of arrest. From the darkest hour in his life he has emerged a new person\npositioned to become a valued member of society. He swiftly recognized his past way of life\nneeded change and took it upon himself to do so. Depression along with the difficulties working\nas a correctional officer took a toll on his mental state where the only solace he sought was in the\nbottle. Being intoxicated and looking for answers on Facebook he now realizes are not the\nanswers he was seeking. Being sober and realizing he has many reasons to live life and be\nhappy. Truly, his turnaround since the inception of this case has been nothing short of\nextraordinary.\n\nc. Factors under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3553(a)\n\nUnder 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 3553 (a), it provides the Court factors to consider in determining an\nappropriate sentence to ensure that it is \u201csufficient, but not greater than necessary.\u201d\nThe factors for the Court to consider is to ensure that any sentence imposed by the Court should\npromote a respect for the law, that the sentence provides adequate deterrence and finally, that the\npublic is protected. All factors can be sufficiently met if a sentence of 120 months imprisonment\nis imposed by the Court. Mr. Hounsell sits before the Court as a first-time offender.\n\nIV. CONCLUSION\n\nFor all the reasons stated within this Sentencing Memorandum as well as those to be argued by\nCounsel at Sentencing, Mr. Hounsell respectfully requests the Court to impose a sentence of 120\nmonths imprisonment which is below the advisory Sentencing Guideline Range and to allow\nself-surrender as he has compiled with all aspects of his pre-trial release and self-surrender will\nprovide him with a more favorable prison classification.\n\nDated: May 12, 2026\n\nLaw Offices of\nEverson & Richards, LLP\n/s\n________________________________\nSteven G. Richards\nAttorney Bar Number 1037545\nAttorney for Defendant\nPost Office Box 8\nCasco, WI 54205-0008\nTelephone: (920) 837-2653\nFax: (920) 837-2924\nE-Mail: sgrlaw@yahoo.com\n\nCase 1:25-cr-00069-WCG Filed 05/12/26 Page 3 of 3 Document 31"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
